  "mood": "Rugged and warm — frontier danger out the gate, the comfort of a town that knows your name",
  "setup_detail": "<!--include:Pacing.EndlessCampaigns-->\n\nOpening scene: open IN the town, grounded in the player's chosen way-in (their fork), at a moment that puts work in front of them — arriving footsore at the gate with coin to earn, or already a known face reading the morning's new postings on the board. Establish the town as alive and lived-in and the wilds as close and dangerous, and end the opening on a concrete job or hook the player can take. Do NOT reveal the bigger threat stirring in the wilds (the crucial-question) — start with small, local, honest work; the larger shape surfaces over many jobs.",
  "detail": "## The Far Marches — the last town before the wild\nThe Marches are the edge of the settled world: one walled frontier town, and beyond its gate a hundred miles of wilds — monster-haunted, weather-bitten, and pocked with the ruins of older things that fell long ago. The town lives off the wilds and off the people brave or desperate enough to go into them: adventurers, trappers, prospectors, relic-hunters. Work is posted on the board at the guild hall, and the work never runs out. This is a home base with your name on a tab, and a hundred miles of trouble out the gate.\n\n## The loop (the engine of the campaign)\nTake a job off the board, go out into the wilds, do the dangerous thing — clear the haunt, delve the ruin, escort the wagon, recover the lost — and come back to spend the coin, mend, and build a name. Jobs come and go; the town stays and remembers. As the player's reputation grows, bigger work opens up, and a bigger shape begins to move behind the small jobs (the crucial-question). The pleasure is the loop: risk out there, comfort and consequence back home.\n\n## The town and the wilds (location skeleton — grow more as the player moves)\nThe town (the home base):\n- **the guild hall & the job board** — the engine; where work is posted, parties form, and pay is collected.\n- **the tavern & its rooms** — the social heart; rumor, recruits, a warm bed, the regulars who know your face.\n- **the temple or shrine** — healing, and the one who patches you up and scolds you for the risks.\n- **the smithy & the market** — gear, repairs, and what your hard-won coin actually buys.\n- **the trade post & the moneylender** — supplies, debts, and the fence who values the odd things you drag back.\n- **the warden's keep & the militia** — the law such as it is, and who posts the dangerous, well-paid jobs.\n- **the palisade gate** — the hard line between safe and not.\n- **the outskirts & the farms** — where the wilds press closest, and trouble arrives first.\nThe wilds (out the gate):\n- **the wilds-edge & the road** — the near country; the starter trouble and the first easy jobs.\n- **the nearest ruin or barrow** — the doorstep dungeon, and lately it has started killing people.\n- **the deep wilds** — the dangerous interior; the bigger ruins, the worse things, the better pay.\n- **the old roads & founding-ruins** — relics of a fallen elder world that built here first (and ties to the crucial-question).\n- **the monster-haunts, the abandoned holdings, the things that should have stayed buried** — the destinations a job leads to.\n\n## DM approach\n- **Run the job board.** Always keep two or three hooks posted, of varying danger and pay; let the player choose, refuse, or haggle. The board is the heartbeat — when one job closes, a new one goes up.\n- **The town is a living home base.** Recurring NPCs who remember the player, react to their growing legend, hire them, help them, resent them, or fall for them. Build found-family among the regulars.\n- **Escalate by reputation, not a clock.** Small, local jobs early; bigger work and the deeper threat surface as the player digs in and makes a name. The wilds reward boldness and punish carelessness, honestly.\n- **Adventurous and warm, not grim.** Real danger in the wilds, real comfort in town. This is build-a-legend, not grimdark misery — setbacks and losses happen, but the through-line is the satisfaction of the work and the place.\n- **The crucial-question is the slow shape.** Behind the week-to-week jobs, something bigger is stirring in the wilds. Keep it hidden; let it surface through the jobs, the ruins, and what the player finds out there.\n\n## The town cast (found-family; some romanceable)\nSeed a couple of recurring regulars from the start and grow the cast as the player puts down roots:\n- **the guild captain** — gruff, fair, knows everyone's business and every job's catch; the player's main line to work and a steady presence. Romanceable: respect earned in the field, warming into more.\n- **the temple healer** — patches the player back together, scolds them for the risks, keeps the town's small mercies running; the town's heart. Romanceable: worry-and-warmth.\nAdd more as ties form — a rival adventurer who needles and respects them, a tavern-keeper who banks their secrets, a prospector with half a map. Romance is available but never forced; the hooks are named, the people are drawn to be wanted, and any bond grows at the player's pace.\n\nPacing: open-ended and serialized (see setup) — the job board is the rhythm, the town persists, arcs come and go. A campaign runs as long as the player keeps taking work.",
